\section*{Introduction}

Teaching methodologies have evolved significantly with the advent of digital technologies. While traditional classroom settings have long been the standard, virtual classrooms have gained prominence, especially in the wake of global events such as the COVID-19 pandemic. This paper explores the differences and similarities between teaching methodologies in virtual and conventional classrooms, highlighting the advantages and disadvantages of each in the context of their unique environments.

\section{Differences Between Virtual and Conventional Classrooms}

\subsection{1. Environment and Medium of Interaction}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Conventional Classroom}: Interaction is face-to-face, with physical presence and non-verbal cues (e.g., body language, eye contact) playing a critical role.
    \item \textbf{Virtual Classroom}: Interaction occurs via digital platforms (e.g., Zoom, Microsoft Teams, Google Meet), relying on audio, video, and text-based communication.

    \textbf{Example:} In a traditional classroom, a teacher can easily gauge a student's confusion by observing their body language. In a virtual setting, this may be more challenging without webcam access or active participation.

\end{itemize}

\subsection{2. Flexibility and Access}
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Conventional Classroom}: Limited by physical location and fixed schedules. Students must attend at specific times and places.
    \item \textbf{Virtual Classroom}: Offers greater flexibility in terms of time and location. Students can access content from anywhere with an internet connection.

    \textbf{Example:} A student in a remote area can participate in an online course without needing to travel, whereas a traditional class would require them to commute.

